{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2e3027ff-c37e-4d7c-a635-04467bc28bf7","content":"In .NET 10 (Android 15 / API 35), edge-to-edge is enforced and `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` is fully removed. The replacement is the **WindowInsets** API.\n\n**In `Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs`:**\n\n```csharp\nusing Android.OS;\nusing Android.Views;\nusing AndroidX.Core.View;\n\nprotected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)\n{\n    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);\n\n    var content = Window!.DecorView.FindViewById(Android.Resource.Id.Content)!;\n\n    ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(content, new KeyboardInsetsListener());\n}\n\nprivate class KeyboardInsetsListener : Java.Lang.Object, IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener\n{\n    public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(View v, WindowInsetsCompat insets)\n    {\n        var ime = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());\n        var bars = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.SystemBars());\n\n        // Use whichever bottom inset is larger — keyboard or nav bar\n        v.SetPadding(0, 0, 0, Math.Max(ime.Bottom, bars.Bottom));\n\n        return insets;\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Why this works:** Instead of the old \"resize the window\" behavior, Android 15 reports the keyboard as a **window inset**. The listener fires when the keyboard opens/closes and adjusts the bottom padding of your root content view so your input bar stays visible.\n\n**Also remove** any old code like:\n```csharp\n// Delete this — it's a no-op on API 35+\nApp.Current.On<Android>().UseWindowSoftInputModeAdjust(WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize);\n```\n\nIf you're also targeting iOS, it handles keyboard avoidance automatically via `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll` — no extra code needed.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"126891d3-75cb-40ba-bd9a-2bf890035bcd","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET MAUI issue where the keyboard covers the text input at the bottom of the screen. They mention that `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` worked in .NET 9 but doesn't work in .NET 10.\n\nThis is a known change in .NET MAUI. In .NET 10 (which targets Android 15+ / API 35+), edge-to-edge display is enforced by default, and the old `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` approach was deprecated in Android API 30 and fully removed in API 35.\n\nThe solution in .NET 10 / Android 15+ is to use the new `WindowInsets` API and handle keyboard (IME) insets properly. \n\nIn .NET 10, the recommended approach is to use `ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener` to handle insets, or work with `ImeInsets` directly to adjust the layout when the keyboard appears. and you can opt into automatic keyboard handling. For .NET MAUI on .NET 10 targeting Android 15+, I'm setting up a window insets listener in the Android platform code to handle IME insets properly. The simpler approach is to leverage MAUI's built-in edge-to-edge support by removing any manual `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust` code and ensuring the MainActivity is configured correctly.\n\nFor a practical solution, I'd wrap the content in a ScrollView since MAUI handles keyboard interactions better that way, then set up platform-specific inset handling on Android by attaching a window insets listener to the content view in MainActivity.\n\nSetting up inset listener... I'm realizing the landscape has shifted with .NET MAUI .NET 10 — they've introduced edge-to-edge support by default on Android 15+, and the old `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust` is now obsolete. The recommended path forward is using WindowInsets directly rather than relying on deprecated manifest settings, since `adjustResize` itself is deprecated on API 35.","outputTokens":1804,"requestId":"143C:16C0F7:2ECFB6:35C9C3:6A03CF3C"},"id":"880e53ff-bd72-40c4-86ac-b248537296b1","timestamp":"2026-05-13T01:09:51.724Z","parentId":"37147d81-8140-44ed-8eaf-a8da8c527363"}
